<dl id="un1013h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1013">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1013h"> (NLI.3) 13(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the great yogin of the gods <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The &ldquo;cult of the left hand&rdquo; is, however, best known as a technical term in India, in use among the T&amacr;ntrikas, or practisers of the Tantras. The Tantras (= Doctrines, Rules) are religious treatises teaching magical and mystical formularies for the theurgical cult of the deities, or the attainment of superhuman powers; they are mostly in the form of dialogues between Shiva, <mark>the Great Yogin of the Gods</mark>, and his Shakti, Spouse or Power, Durg&amacr;. <small> <a name="THRdec1908" href="/udra/udex.htm#THRdec1908"><cite title="source">The Theosophical Review</cite></a> (December 1908), G. R. S. M., &ldquo;Queries and Notes. VI&rdquo; 368</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Copied to <a name="s15021al" href="s15all.htm#s15021al">Sheet 15.021(al)</a> for <cite>UG</cite> 15.2268f. </mm> </dd></dl>
